BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 566.20 Tm (Alright, let's really feel this problem, because it is the heart of why we are here. Look at the screen.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 551.00 Tm (On the left, our program is running. We have an ArrayList of students, and we have added five of) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 535.80 Tm (them. We print the size, and it says five. Everything looks perfect.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 515.60 Tm (Now imagine this is a real application at your company, and it has been running all day. Maybe) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 500.40 Tm (there are not five students, but five thousand. Then in the evening, the server restarts - maybe) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 485.20 Tm (there was a software update, maybe the power flickered, maybe somebody just rebooted the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 470.00 Tm (machine. Look at the right panel now. After the restart, the same list is... empty. Zero. All five) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 454.80 Tm (thousand records, gone.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 434.60 Tm (Why did that happen? Because that list lived in RAM - the computer's short-term memory. And) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 419.40 Tm (RAM is like writing on a whiteboard. It is fast and convenient, but the moment the power goes,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 404.20 Tm (somebody wipes the whiteboard clean.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 384.00 Tm (So here is the one sentence I want you to take from this slide. In-memory data lives only as long) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 368.80 Tm (as the program lives. A database, on the other hand, is like writing in a permanent notebook - it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 353.60 Tm (stays there tomorrow, next week, after any restart. And JDBC is the pen that lets Java write into) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 338.40 Tm (that notebook. Make sense? Good - let's see how it works.) Tj ET
