BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 253.00 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 237.00 Tm (Now let's see how the pieces stack up, top to bottom. Don't be intimidated by the word) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 221.80 Tm ('architecture' - it just means 'what talks to what'. Let me walk you down the ladder.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 201.60 Tm (At the very top is your Java application - that is the code you write. Just below it is the JDBC API -) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 186.40 Tm (those interfaces we just talked about, the standard methods in java dot s-q-l.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 166.20 Tm (Next comes a very important piece called the DriverManager. Think of the DriverManager as a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 151.00 Tm (receptionist or a matchmaker. You walk up and say, 'I want to connect to this database,' and you) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 135.80 Tm (hand it an address. The DriverManager looks at that address, figures out which driver knows how) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 120.60 Tm (to talk to that database, and connects you to the right one. You do not have to pick the driver) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 105.40 Tm (yourself - it does that for you.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 85.20 Tm (Below the DriverManager is the actual driver - the JAR file from the database company - and at) Tj ET
