BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 520.60 Tm (love to ask about all four, and you will sometimes see the old ones in very old projects, so let me) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 505.40 Tm (give you a quick tour. Don't memorise the details - just get the story.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 485.20 Tm (Type one was the JDBC-ODBC bridge. It was a translator that converted Java calls into something) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 470.00 Tm (older called ODBC. It was slow and clunky, and honestly, it was removed from Java back in) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 454.80 Tm (version eight. So it is basically a museum piece now.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 434.60 Tm (Type two used the database's own native libraries, written in C or C-plus-plus, which meant you) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 419.40 Tm (had to install extra software on every machine. A bit of a headache, so it is rare today.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 399.20 Tm (Type three sent everything through a middle-man server. You still find it in some big old enterprise) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 384.00 Tm (systems.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 363.80 Tm (And then type four - this is the one. It is a pure Java driver, a single JAR file, that talks directly to) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 348.60 Tm (the database. No extra installation, no middle-man, works everywhere Java works. This is what) Tj ET
