BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 555.60 Tm (On the left is the old way, called Statement. Look at how the query is built - we glue strings) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 540.40 Tm (together with plus signs, sticking the user's data right into the middle of the SQL text. It works, but) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 525.20 Tm (it has problems: it is messy with all those quotes, the database has to re-read and re-understand it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 510.00 Tm (every single time, and - the big one - it is dangerously open to attack. We will see that in two) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 494.80 Tm (minutes.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 474.60 Tm (On the right is the right way, called PreparedStatement. Notice we do not glue the values in.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 459.40 Tm (Instead we write the query with little placeholders - those question marks. Then we fill in the values) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 444.20 Tm (separately, using setInt, setString, and so on. The query is like a form with blank boxes, and we fill) Tj ET
