BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 415.00 Tm (So that was the scary part. Here is the wonderful part - the fix is almost embarrassingly simple.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 399.80 Tm (Look at the right panel. It is the same login, but written with a PreparedStatement and those) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 384.60 Tm (question-mark placeholders, and we fill in the username and password with setString.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 364.40 Tm (Now let me explain why this completely stops the attack, because this is the bit I really want you to) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 349.20 Tm (understand. With a PreparedStatement, the driver sends two separate things to the database: first) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 334.00 Tm (the query shape with the blanks, and then, separately, the values. The database treats those) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 318.80 Tm (values as pure data - just text to search for - never as commands.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 298.60 Tm (So when the attacker types admin-quote-dash-dash, the database does not get confused. It simply) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 283.40 Tm (goes and looks for a user whose name is literally the funny text 'admin-quote-dash-dash'. Of) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 268.20 Tm (course, no such user exists, so the login just fails. The quote can no longer break out and mess) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 253.00 Tm (with the query, because the database was never trying to read it as SQL in the first place.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 232.80 Tm (Let me give you an analogy. With the old way, you were shouting your data and your commands) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 217.60 Tm (together, and the attacker could sneak a command into the shout. With a PreparedStatement, you) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 202.40 Tm (hand the database a sealed form - the boxes are clearly marked as 'data only', and nothing written) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 187.20 Tm (in a box is ever treated as an instruction.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 167.00 Tm (So here is the rule, and it is not a suggestion, it is a rule: never, ever use plain Statement for) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 151.80 Tm (anything that includes input from a user. Always use PreparedStatement. No exceptions.) Tj ET
